    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-02-06T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-02-06T02:00:00-05:00" n="465"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d465">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.515/1001: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Peck</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-02-06T15:00:00+08:00"
                            >February 6, 1936—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received February 6—9:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>31. McDaniel<note n="6" xml:id="d465fn6">C. Yates McDaniel, Associated Press
                        correspondent at Nanking.</note> was informed by Jabin Hsu,<note n="7"
                        xml:id="d465fn7">Director of General Affairs, Chinese Ministry of
                        Finance.</note> February 6, 11 a.m. that Suma<note n="8" xml:id="d465fn8"
                        >Yakichiro Suma, First Secretary of the Japanese Embassy in China.</note>
                    has just told him that when in Shanghai February 5 he had personally told
                    Leith-Ross that in view of the imminent <hi rend="italic">rapprochement</hi>
                    between Japan and China it would not be fitting for any other nation to offer
                    advice or otherwise intervene in China’s currency or fiscal matters. Suma said
                    he had called to tell Kung<note n="9" xml:id="d465fn9">H. H. Kung, Chinese
                        Minister of Finance.</note> about this. However, Suma told Hsu the Japanese
                    Government does not disapprove of the recent bond conversion scheme and believes
                    there was nothing else for the Chinese Government to do.</p>
                <p>Repeated to the Embassy and the Department.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Peck</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
